<DOC><DOCNO> AP890705-0212 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2302EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Sandamp;LFraud     07-05 0458</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Sandamp;L Fraud,0474</SECOND><HEAD>Four Former Thrift Executives Named In Bank Fraud Indictments</HEAD><BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal officials announced Wednesday that threeformer thrift executive agreed to plead guilty to bank fraud chargesand that a former savings and loan president was indicted on threesimilar counts.   The latest charges bring to 26 the number of people indicted thisyear by the Dallas Bank Fraud Task Force, compared with 23 people inall of 1988. The task force investigates cases in North Texas, saidBob Gillham, agent-in-charge of the Dallas FBI office.   Of those indicted, 20 have been senior officers, owners or vicepresidents of banks or savings and loans, Gillham said.   The three-count indictment names Bob R. Franks, former presidentand director of Northpark Savings Association in Richardson, andaccuses him of scheming to defraud Northpark of funds andmisapplying $138,000 of the thrift's money.   Franks faces up to 15 years in prison and a $500,000 fine.   The three who agreed to plead guilty were:   _John H. Roberts Jr., former president and owner of SummitSavings Association of Dallas, to charges of bank fraud andmisapplication of funds. The indictment, filed June 8, alleges heschemed to defraud Summit of $4.5 million and misapplied $1 millionof Summit funds.   Federal officials contend Roberts arranged for a borrower toobtain a loan to buy a jet for Roberts' personal use. The indictmentsaid Roberts planned to have Summit make a $200,000 downpayment onthe airplane and charge the payment as a draw against a prior $2.5million construction loan to a Summit borrower, without theborrower's knowledge or consent.   Roberts faces up to 10 years in prison and a $15,000 fine ortwice the amount of the gain or loss.   _Joseph R. Smith, former vice president and loan officer ofSunbelt Savings Association of Dallas, to one count of conspiracy todefraud the Federal Home Loan Bank Board by disguising the truefinancial condition of Sunbelt's loan portfolio and defrauding theInternal Revenue Service.   The indictment alleges Smith received $125,000 from a Sunbeltreal estate transaction but Smith did not report it on his 1985 taxreturns.   Smith faces up to five years' imprisonment and a $250,000 fine ortwice the amount of the gain or loss.   _Kenneth Clive Hood, former board chairman of Century Investmentsand former vice president of Western Savings Association, to twocounts of conspiring to defraud the IRS by creating artificiallosses for Amchase Financial Corp. to offset large income gains.   Hood also agreed to plead guilty to making a false statement inconnection with an $11.4 million loan from Sunbelt SavingsAssociation.   He faces up to seven years in prison and a fine of $500,000.</TEXT></DOC>